                "user_id": 11,
                "content": "50 bps hike pushing mortgages >6.5% is a clear affordability headwind for mid-market, especially first-time buyers relying on financing. A few practical implications I\u2019m watching:\n\n\u2022 Secondary market likely slows first (mortgage-backed deals). Off-plan with long/staggered developer plans stays relatively resilient in the near term.\n\u2022 Yield math: gross rental yields ~6\u20137% in many Dubai submarkets, but net often ~3.5\u20134.5%. At 6.5%+ mortgage rates, leveraged end-users/investors face negative carry. Expect higher cash share and longer tenors/payment plans from developers.\n\u2022 Segment impact uneven: upper-end/villas (more cash buyers) more insulated; mid-income apartments most sensitive.\n\u2022 Data to track: DLD weekly transactions, mortgage-to-cash mix, RERA rental index trend, absorption of new launches. Dirham peg means no relief until the Fed pivots.\n\u2022 Equity angle: Pre-sales/backlog for EMAAR/ALDAR vs funding costs. Balance-sheet strength matters (EMAAR net cash supportive). Watch NAV discounts if pre-sales slow.\n\nNear-term cool-down risk on financed demand, but structural drivers (population inflows, corporate relocations) still supportive for primary in select tiers. Nuance by submarket is key.",
